{"title_page": "William 'Gentleman' Smith", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = William Smith\n| image                 =William 'Gentleman' Smith, 1819.png\n| imagesize             = 250px\n| caption               = A portrait of Smith by [[John Jackson (painter)|John Jackson]] c. 1819, in the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] in London.\n| birth_name             =\n| birth_date             = 1730\n| birth_place            = London\n| death_date             = 13 September 1819\n| death_place            = [[Bury St Edmunds]]\n| othername             = William \"Gentleman\" Smith\n| occupation            = Actor\n| yearsactive           = 1753\u20131758\n| spouse                = Kelland Courtnay<br/>Miss Newson\n| domesticpartner       =\n}}\n\n'''William Smith''' (1730 \u2013 13 September 1819), known as '''\"Gentleman Smith\"''', was a celebrated English actor of the 18th century who worked with [[David Garrick]], and was the original creator of the role of Charles Surface in [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s ''[[The School for Scandal]]''.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nWilliam Smith was born in London in 1730. His father, intending that he should enter the church, sent him to [[Eton College]] in 1737 and then to [[St John's College, Cambridge]] in 1748.<ref>{{acad|id=SMT747W2|name=Smith, William}}</ref> The vivacious spirit for which he was well known at Eton led him into problems at Cambridge. One evening he drank too freely with some friends and, being pursued by a proctor, he unwisely snapped an unloaded pistol at him. He refused the punishment that was imposed, and quit the University to avoid expulsion.<ref>'\"Gentleman Smith\", the original Charles Surface', in [[William Hone]] (ed.), ''The Every-Day Book: or, The Guide to the Year'' (London 1825), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8CEIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1287\u20131291] (Google).</ref>\n\n===Covent Garden 1753\u20131774===\nSmith was inclined towards the stage: upon arrival in London, he applied to [[John Rich (producer)|John Rich]] at the original [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]] Theatre, where he first appeared in January 1753 in the role of Theodosius (in [[Nathaniel Lee]]'s tragedy of ''The Force of Love''<ref>See (Obituary notice of William Smith) ''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), a performance attended by many of his college friends in a spirit of solidarity. He next appeared as Polydore in [[Thomas Otway]]'s ''[[The Orphan (play)|The Orphan]]'', Southampton in ''The Earl of Essex'', and Dolabella in [[John Dryden]]'s ''[[All For Love (play)|All for Love]]''. Having taken various subordinate roles in casts led by Mrs. Cibber and [[Spranger Barry]] (whose pupil he had effectively become<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), on Barry's retirement he took on many of that actor's principal parts. If he had defects, they were generally overlooked by his audiences, who admired his upright and independent private life. The poet [[Charles Churchill (satirist)|Charles Churchill]], in his \"Rosciad\" satire of 1761, said of him: \"Smith the genteel, the airy, and the smart; Smith should still go to school to learn his part.\" Smith was at Covent Garden for 22 years.\n  \n===Drury Lane 1774\u20131788===\nAt the end of season in 1774 he and the actress [[Elizabeth Hartley (actress)|Elizabeth Hartley]], who played his on-stage lover in ''Henry II or The Fall of Rosamond'', caused a scandal when they absconded to France. They travelled on to [[Cork (city)|Cork, Ireland]] where they acted together. They both returned to London for the autumn season, Hartley to continue at Covent Garden and Smith to Drury Lane.<ref>{{cite book|title=Habgood to Houbert: Volume 7 of A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and Other Stage Personnel in London, 1660-1800|year=1982|publisher=SIU Press|isbn=9780809309184|author=Edward A. Langhans|pages=156\u2013164}}</ref> Garrick having engaged him for [[Drury Lane]], he remained there until retirement in 1788. Though for a long time he played lead roles in tragedy, for which he had a suitably tall and well-proportioned figure, his facial features lacked the flexibility and expressiveness, and his vocal delivery was somewhat too harsh and monotonous, to be considered ideal. However, he won popularity as [[Richard III (play)|Richard III]], [[Henry IV, Part 1|Hotspur]], and Hastings, and was also admired in the roles of Kitely (''[[Every Man in his Humour]]'', in which he was preferred to Garrick<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), Archer, and Oakly. It was said that he prided himself on the reflection that he was never called upon to perform in an [[after-piece]], or to pass through a trapdoor in any entrance or exit on the stage.<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', as above.</ref>\n\n===Charles Surface===\nSmith's masterpiece was his impersonation of Charles Surface in [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s ''[[The School for Scandal]]'', which won the highest praise for originality, boldness of conception, truth, freedom, ease, and gracefulness of action and manner.<ref>'\"Gentleman Smith\", the original Charles Surface', in [[William Hone]] (ed.), ''The Every-Day Book: or, The Guide to the Year'' (London 1825), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8CEIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1287\u20131291] (Google).</ref> He is mentioned favourably in [[Charles Lamb (writer)|Charles Lamb]]'s ''[[Essays of Elia]]'', in the \"Essay upon Old Actors\". On 9 March 1788, after a performance of [[Hamlet]], Smith announced his intention to retire and \"resign the sprightly Charles to abler hands and younger heads\". After a performance of the role on 9 June 1788, he gave his farewell speech, though he did appear once more in 1798 in a benefit performance for his friend [[Thomas King (actor)|Thomas King]], when, 'having grown very lusty, he went through the character with that spirit, ease, and elegance, for which he was unequalled.'<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>\n\n==Personal life and retirement==\nIn his early days, Smith was often distracted from his professional work by his love of fox-hunting.<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', as above.</ref> He first married the sister of the [[Earl of Sandwich]], Mrs Kelland Courtnay (a widow), who died in 1762. His elopement to Ireland with Elizabeth Hartley followed. In later life he was remarried, to Miss Newson of [[Leiston]] in Suffolk. (Through the second marriage in the Newson family is traced a relationship to [[Hamlet Watling]], whose brother Edwin also married a daughter of Smith's<ref>Hamlet Watling, 'Suffolk Heraldry & Genealogy in 12 Vols' (MS, [[Ipswich Museum]], Christchurch Mansion) Vol 8.</ref>). Smith died at [[Bury St Edmunds]] on 13 September 1819 in his 89th year. There his elegant figure was remembered as always wearing a white hat edged with green, a blue coat, figured waistcoat, fustian coloured breeches, and gaiters to match, and carrying a gold-headed cane. He was loved by the youngsters of Bury whom he often obliged with sweets from the candy-shop.<ref>William Hone, ''The Every-Day Book'' (London, 1830), Volume I, 1287\u20131291.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n*Christian Deelman, 'The original cast of The School for Scandal', ''The Review of English Studies'' 1962 XIII(51), pp.&nbsp;257\u2013266.\n*''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' 1911.\n*{{DNB|prescript=|wstitle=Smith, William (1730?-1819)|volume=53|last=Knight|first=John Joseph|authorlink=}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, William Gentleman}}\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:1730 births]]\n[[Category:1819 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = William Smith\n| image                 =William 'Gentleman' Smith, 1819.png\n| imagesize             = 250px\n| caption               = A portrait of Smith by [[John Jackson (painter)|John Jackson]] c. 1819, in the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] in London.\n| birth_name             =\n| birth_date             = 1730\n| birth_place            = London\n| death_date             = 13 September 1819\n| death_place            = [[Bury St Edmunds]]\n| othername             = William \"Gentleman\" Smith\n| occupation            = Actor\n| yearsactive           = 1753\u20131758\n| spouse                = Kelland Courtnay<br/>Miss Newson\n| domesticpartner       =\n}}\n\n'''William Smith''' (1730 \u2013 13 September 1819), known as '''\"Gentleman Smith\"''', was a celebrated English actor of the 18th century who worked with [[David Garrick]], and was the original creator of the role of Charles Surface in [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s ''[[The School for Scandal]]''.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nWilliam Smith was born in London in 1730. His father, intending that he should enter the church, sent him to [[Eton College]] in 1737 and then to [[St John's College, Cambridge]] in 1748.<ref>{{acad|id=SMT747W2|name=Smith, William}}</ref> The vivacious spirit for which he was well known at Eton led him into problems at Cambridge. One evening he drank too freely with some friends and, being pursued by a proctor, he unwisely snapped an unloaded pistol at him. He refused the punishment that was imposed, and quit the University to avoid expulsion.\n\n===Covent Garden 1753\u20131774===\nSmith was inclined towards the stage: upon arrival in London, he applied to [[John Rich (producer)|John Rich]] at the original [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]] Theatre, where he first appeared in January 1753 in the role of Theodosius (in [[Nathaniel Lee]]'s tragedy of ''The Force of Love''<ref>See (Obituary notice of William Smith) ''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), a performance attended by many of his college friends in a spirit of solidarity. He next appeared as Polydore in [[Thomas Otway]]'s ''[[The Orphan (play)|The Orphan]]'', Southampton in ''The Earl of Essex'', and Dolabella in [[John Dryden]]'s ''[[All For Love (play)|All for Love]]''. Having taken various subordinate roles in casts led by Mrs. Cibber and [[Spranger Barry]] (whose pupil he had effectively become<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), on Barry's retirement he took on many of that actor's principal parts. If he had defects, they were generally overlooked by his audiences, who admired his upright and independent private life. The poet [[Charles Churchill (satirist)|Charles Churchill]], in his \"Rosciad\" satire of 1761, said of him: \"Smith the genteel, the airy, and the smart; Smith should still go to school to learn his part.\" Smith was at Covent Garden for 22 years.\n  \n===Drury Lane 1774\u20131788===\nAt the end of season in 1774 he and the actress [[Elizabeth Hartley (actress)|Elizabeth Hartley]], who played his on-stage lover in ''Henry II or The Fall of Rosamond'', caused a scandal when they absconded to France. They travelled on to [[Cork (city)|Cork, Ireland]] where they acted together. They both returned to London for the autumn season, Hartley to continue at Covent Garden and Smith to Drury Lane.<ref>{{cite book|title=Habgood to Houbert: Volume 7 of A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and Other Stage Personnel in London, 1660-1800|year=1982|publisher=SIU Press|isbn=9780809309184|author=Edward A. Langhans|pages=156\u2013164}}</ref> Garrick having engaged him for [[Drury Lane]], he remained there until retirement in 1788. Though for a long time he played lead roles in tragedy, for which he had a suitably tall and well-proportioned figure, his facial features lacked the flexibility and expressiveness, and his vocal delivery was somewhat too harsh and monotonous, to be considered ideal. However, he won popularity as [[Richard III (play)|Richard III]], [[Henry IV, Part 1|Hotspur]], and Hastings, and was also admired in the roles of Kitely (''[[Every Man in his Humour]]'', in which he was preferred to Garrick<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>), Archer, and Oakly. It was said that he prided himself on the reflection that he was never called upon to perform in an [[after-piece]], or to pass through a trapdoor in any entrance or exit on the stage.<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', as above.</ref>\n\n===Charles Surface===\nSmith's masterpiece was his impersonation of Charles Surface in [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s ''[[The School for Scandal]]'', which won the highest praise for originality, boldness of conception, truth, freedom, ease, and gracefulness of action and manner.<ref>'\"Gentleman Smith\", the original Charles Surface', in [[William Hone]] (ed.), ''The Every-Day Book: or, The Guide to the Year'' (London 1825), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8CEIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1287\u20131291] (Google).</ref> He is mentioned favourably in [[Charles Lamb (writer)|Charles Lamb]]'s ''[[Essays of Elia]]'', in the \"Essay upon Old Actors\". On 9 March 1788, after a performance of [[Hamlet]], Smith announced his intention to retire and \"resign the sprightly Charles to abler hands and younger heads\". After a performance of the role on 9 June 1788, he gave his farewell speech, though he did appear once more in 1798 in a benefit performance for his friend [[Thomas King (actor)|Thomas King]], when, 'having grown very lusty, he went through the character with that spirit, ease, and elegance, for which he was unequalled.'<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', 9 October 1819, p. 4.</ref>\n\n==Personal life and retirement==\nIn his early days, Smith was often distracted from his professional work by his love of fox-hunting.<ref>''Ipswich Journal'', as above.</ref> He first married the sister of the [[Earl of Sandwich]], Mrs Kelland Courtnay (a widow), who died in 1762. His elopement to Ireland with Elizabeth Hartley followed. In later life he was remarried, to Miss Newson of [[Leiston]] in Suffolk. (Through the second marriage in the Newson family is traced a relationship to [[Hamlet Watling]], whose brother Edwin also married a daughter of Smith's<ref>Hamlet Watling, 'Suffolk Heraldry & Genealogy in 12 Vols' (MS, [[Ipswich Museum]], Christchurch Mansion) Vol 8.</ref>). Smith died at [[Bury St Edmunds]] on 13 September 1819 in his 89th year. There his elegant figure was remembered as always wearing a white hat edged with green, a blue coat, figured waistcoat, fustian coloured breeches, and gaiters to match, and carrying a gold-headed cane. He was loved by the youngsters of Bury whom he often obliged with sweets from the candy-shop.<ref>William Hone, ''The Every-Day Book'' (London, 1830), Volume I, 1287\u20131291.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n*Christian Deelman, 'The original cast of The School for Scandal', ''The Review of English Studies'' 1962 XIII(51), pp.&nbsp;257\u2013266.\n*''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' 1911.\n*{{DNB|prescript=|wstitle=Smith, William (1730?-1819)|volume=53|last=Knight|first=John Joseph|authorlink=}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, William Gentleman}}\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:1730 births]]\n[[Category:1819 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:full ref near start", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_%27Gentleman%27_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Shirana Shahbazi", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Shirana Shahbazi <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Shirana Shahbazi Rudolfinum-2.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1974}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      =\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = \n| education        = [[Dortmund University of Applied Sciences and Arts]], [[Zurich University of the Arts]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          =\n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n'''Shirana Shahbazi''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0634\u0647\u0628\u0627\u0632\u06cc}}; born 1974) is an Iranian-born photographer who now lives in Switzerland. Her work includes installations and large prints of conceptual photography.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Tehran, Shahbazi move to Germany in 1985, studying photography and design at the [[Dortmund University of Applied Sciences and Arts|University of Applied Sciences and Arts]] in [[Dortmund]] from 1995 to 1997. From 1997 to 2000, Shahbazi attended the [[Zurich University of the Arts]], Switzerland, specializing in photography.<ref name=\":0\" /> She currently lives and works in Zurich. Her first successful sequence ''Goftare Nik/Good Words'' of color photographs taken in Iran (published as a book in 2001 with Hatje Cantz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hatjecantz.de/shirana-shahbazi-3697-1.html?article_id=3697&clang=1|title=Shirana Shahbazi {{!}} Photography {{!}} Hatje Cantz|website=www.hatjecantz.de|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>) led to the Citibank Private Bank Photography Prize in 2002.<ref>[http://www.artdaily.com/index.asp?int_sec=11&int_new=27833&int_modo=2 \"Hammer Projects: Shirana Shahbazi Opens at The Hammer Museum\"], artdaily.org. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/detail/exhibition_id/150 Chris Balaschak, \"Shirana Shahbazi\"], Hammer. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> In 2002, she presented a series of images of Switzerland titled ''The Garden''. At the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2003, she presented ''The Annunciation'', an enormous installation in the central pavilion with murals by Iranian painters based on her photographs and a ceiling of lilies.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/shirana_shahbazi/ \"Shirana Shahbazi\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104132245/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/shirana_shahbazi/ |date=2013-01-04 }}, ''frieze'', April 2005. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> She is the recipient of 2019 [[Swiss Art Awards|Prix Meret Oppenheim]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/2019/03/14/prix-meret-oppenheim-shirana-shahbazi-among-winners/|title=Photographer Shirana Shahbazi Among Winners of 2019 Prix Meret\u00a0Oppenheim|last=Greenberger|first=Alex|date=2019-03-14|website=ARTnews|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nPresented as an installation, her ''Meanwhile'' series (2007), combines everyday images of landscapes, portraits and still lifes from her world travels, one of her images expanded to poster size by an Iranian billboard artist. Other photographs are reproduced as paintings or even carpets.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.art-it.jp/review_detail.php?id=21 Olivia Qusaibaty, \"Shirana Shahbazi: Meanwhile\"], Art It. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> The exhibition ''Then Again'' (2012)  at the [[Fotomuseum Winterthur]] presents 18 large-format works demonstrating how a photograph can be transformed from a depiction of reality into a geometric abstraction.<ref>[http://www.galerierudolfinum.cz/en/exhibition/shirana-shahbazi \"Shirana Shahbazi: Then Again\"], Galerie Rudolfinum. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> As discussed by Adam Jasper's review in Artforum, Shahbazi's photographs are true abstractions in that they are less a representational photograph than they are actual objects themselves, highly constructed. Continuing to work in analog photographic methods, some of Shabazi's newest works exist as geometric shapes captured on polished mirrors with thin films of color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/reviews/201710/shirana-shahbazi-72516|title=Adam Jasper on Shirana Shahbazi|website=www.artforum.com|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nShahbazi's work has been widely exhibited all over the world. In 2007, Shabhazi exhibited ''Meanwhile'' at the [[Swiss Institute Contemporary Art New York|Swiss Institute]] in New York City and at the [[Barbican Art Gallery]] London, in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Shahbazi is represented by Galerie Peter Kilchmann, Zurich.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterkilchmann.com/artists/profile/++/name/shirana-shahbazi/id/70/|title=Profile {{!}} www.peterkilchmann.com|website=www.peterkilchmann.com|language=de|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref> The exhibition ''Monstera'' at [[Kunsthalle Bern]] in 2014 was curated by [[Fabrice Stroun]] and [[Tenzing Barshee]]. The artist has been exhibiting regularly since 1997, with her most recent solo exhibition at [[Kunsthaus Hamburg]], in Germany in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" /> Numerous photographs are held in the collection of The Museum of Modern Art, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/28426|title=Shirana Shahbazi {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*Shahbazi, Shirana (2007). [https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-Meanwhile-Kate-Bush/dp/3905829053/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1520543980&sr=8-1&keywords=shirana+shahbazi+meanwhile Meanwhile]. JRP Ringier. {{ISBN|978-3-905829051}}\n*{{cite book|last=Shahbazi|first=Shirana|title=Shirana Shahbazi: Then Again|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4AeeZwEACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Innovative Logistics Llc|isbn=978-3-86930-338-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Shahbazi|first=Shirana|title=Monstera|url=https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-Monstera/dp/3037644001/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1418906072&sr=8-2&keywords=shirana+shahbazi|year=2014|publisher=JRP Ringier|isbn=978-3-0376440-0-3}}\n*Shahbazi, Shirana (2017). ''[https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-First-Things-German/dp/3956793242/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1520543860&sr=8-1&keywords=9783956793240 Shirana Shahbazi : first things first]''. Sternberg Press. {{ISBN|9783956793240}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[:Category:Swiss contemporary artists|Swiss contemporary artists]]\n*[[List of Iranian artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.peterkilchmann.com/artists/profile/++/name/shirana-shahbazi/id/70/ Shirana Shahbazi at Galerie Peter Kilchmann]\n*[http://thebreedersystem.com/artists/shirana-shahbazi-artist-page/ Shirana Shahbazi at The Breeder, Athens]\n*[http://www.swissinstitute.net/2001-2006/Exhibitions/2003_Mir_Monk/shahbazi.htm Michele Robecchi interview with Shirana Shahbazi, Flash Art, November 2003]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shahbazi, Shirana}}\n[[Category:Iranian photographers]]\n[[Category:Iranian women artists]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Women photographers]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:People from Z\u00fcrich]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Swiss contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Iranian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Women conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Shirana Shahbazi <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Shirana Shahbazi Rudolfinum-2.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1974}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      =\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = \n| education        = [[Dortmund University of Applied Sciences and Arts]], [[Zurich University of the Arts]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          =\n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n'''Shirana Shahbazi''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0634\u0647\u0628\u0627\u0632\u06cc}}; born 1974) is an Iranian-born photographer who now lives in Switzerland. Her work includes installations and large prints of conceptual photography.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Tehran, Shahbazi move to Germany in 1985, studying photography and design at the [[Dortmund University of Applied Sciences and Arts|University of Applied Sciences and Arts]] in [[Dortmund]] from 1995 to 1997. From 1997 to 2000, Shahbazi attended the [[Zurich University of the Arts]], Switzerland, specializing in photography.<ref name=\":0\" /> She currently lives and works in Zurich. Her first successful sequence ''Goftare Nik/Good Words'' of color photographs taken in Iran (published as a book in 2001 with Hatje Cantz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hatjecantz.de/shirana-shahbazi-3697-1.html?article_id=3697&clang=1|title=Shirana Shahbazi {{!}} Photography {{!}} Hatje Cantz|website=www.hatjecantz.de|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>) led to the Citibank Private Bank Photography Prize in 2002.<ref>[http://www.artdaily.com/index.asp?int_sec=11&int_new=27833&int_modo=2 \"Hammer Projects: Shirana Shahbazi Opens at The Hammer Museum\"], artdaily.org. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/detail/exhibition_id/150 Chris Balaschak, \"Shirana Shahbazi\"], Hammer. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> In 2002, she presented a series of images of Switzerland titled ''The Garden''. At the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2003, she presented ''The Annunciation'', an enormous installation in the central pavillion with murals by Iranian painters based on her photographs and a ceiling of lilies.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/shirana_shahbazi/ \"Shirana Shahbazi\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104132245/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/shirana_shahbazi/ |date=2013-01-04 }}, ''frieze'', April 2005. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> She is the recipient of 2019 [[Swiss Art Awards|Prix Meret Oppenheim]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/2019/03/14/prix-meret-oppenheim-shirana-shahbazi-among-winners/|title=Photographer Shirana Shahbazi Among Winners of 2019 Prix Meret\u00a0Oppenheim|last=Greenberger|first=Alex|date=2019-03-14|website=ARTnews|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> \n\n==Work==\nPresented as an installation, her ''Meanwhile'' series (2007), combines everyday images of landscapes, portraits and still lifes from her world travels, one of her images expanded to poster size by an Iranian billboard artist. Other photographs are reproduced as paintings or even carpets.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.art-it.jp/review_detail.php?id=21 Olivia Qusaibaty, \"Shirana Shahbazi: Meanwhile\"], Art It. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> The exhibition ''Then Again'' (2012)  at the [[Fotomuseum Winterthur]] presents 18 large-format works demonstrating how a photograph can be transformed from a depiction of reality into a geometric abstraction.<ref>[http://www.galerierudolfinum.cz/en/exhibition/shirana-shahbazi \"Shirana Shahbazi: Then Again\"], Galerie Rudolfinum. Retrieved 23 March 2013.</ref> As discussed by Adam Jasper's review in Artforum, Shahbazi's photographs are true abstractions in that they are less a representational photograph than they are actual objects themselves, highly constructed. Continuing to work in analog photographic methods, some of Shabazi's newest works exist as geometric shapes captured on polished mirrors with thin films of color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/reviews/201710/shirana-shahbazi-72516|title=Adam Jasper on Shirana Shahbazi|website=www.artforum.com|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nShahbazi's work has been widely exhibited all over the world. In 2007, Shabhazi exhibited ''Meanwhile'' at the [[Swiss Institute Contemporary Art New York|Swiss Institute]] in New York City and at the [[Barbican Art Gallery]] London, in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> Shahbazi is represented by Galerie Peter Kilchmann, Zurich.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterkilchmann.com/artists/profile/++/name/shirana-shahbazi/id/70/|title=Profile {{!}} www.peterkilchmann.com|website=www.peterkilchmann.com|language=de|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref> The exhibition ''Monstera'' at [[Kunsthalle Bern]] in 2014 was curated by [[Fabrice Stroun]] and [[Tenzing Barshee]]. The artist has been exhibiting regularly since 1997, with her most recent solo exhibition at [[Kunsthaus Hamburg]], in Germany in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" /> Numerous photographs are held in the collection of The Museum of Modern Art, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/28426|title=Shirana Shahbazi {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*Shahbazi, Shirana (2007). [https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-Meanwhile-Kate-Bush/dp/3905829053/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1520543980&sr=8-1&keywords=shirana+shahbazi+meanwhile Meanwhile]. JRP Ringier. {{ISBN|978-3-905829051}}\n*{{cite book|last=Shahbazi|first=Shirana|title=Shirana Shahbazi: Then Again|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4AeeZwEACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Innovative Logistics Llc|isbn=978-3-86930-338-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Shahbazi|first=Shirana|title=Monstera|url=https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-Monstera/dp/3037644001/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1418906072&sr=8-2&keywords=shirana+shahbazi|year=2014|publisher=JRP Ringier|isbn=978-3-0376440-0-3}}\n*Shahbazi, Shirana (2017). ''[https://www.amazon.com/Shirana-Shahbazi-First-Things-German/dp/3956793242/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1520543860&sr=8-1&keywords=9783956793240 Shirana Shahbazi : first things first]''. Sternberg Press. {{ISBN|9783956793240}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[:Category:Swiss contemporary artists|Swiss contemporary artists]]\n*[[List of Iranian artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.peterkilchmann.com/artists/profile/++/name/shirana-shahbazi/id/70/ Shirana Shahbazi at Galerie Peter Kilchmann]\n*[http://thebreedersystem.com/artists/shirana-shahbazi-artist-page/ Shirana Shahbazi at The Breeder, Athens]\n*[http://www.swissinstitute.net/2001-2006/Exhibitions/2003_Mir_Monk/shahbazi.htm Michele Robecchi interview with Shirana Shahbazi, Flash Art, November 2003]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shahbazi, Shirana}}\n[[Category:Iranian photographers]]\n[[Category:Iranian women artists]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Women photographers]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:People from Z\u00fcrich]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Swiss contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Iranian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Women conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: pavillion \u2192 pavilion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shirana_Shahbazi"}
{"title_page": "Ninemile Canyon (Utah)", "text_new": "{{Coord|39|46|35|N|110|30|0|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n[[File:Daddycanyon1.jpeg|thumb|The Daddy Canyon area of Ninemile Canyon, November 2007]]\n[[File:NineMileCanyon map.png|thumb|Map of Ninemile Canyon, from [[National Scenic Byway]]s Program]]\n\n'''Ninemile Canyon''' (also '''Nine Mile Canyon''') is a [[canyon]], approximately {{convert|40|mi|km}} long, located in [[Carbon County, Utah|Carbon]] and [[Duchesne County, Utah|Duchesne]] counties in eastern [[Utah]], United States. Promoted as \"the world\u2019s longest art gallery\", the canyon is known for its extensive [[rock art]], most of it created by the [[Fremont culture]] and the [[Ute tribe|Ute]] people. The rock art, shelters, and [[granary|granaries]] left behind by the Fremont make Ninemile Canyon a destination for [[archaeology|archaeologists]] and tourists alike.\n\nThe canyon became a main [[transport corridor]] in the region during the 1880s. Settlers established a number of [[ranch]]es in Ninemile Canyon, and even a short-lived town named [[Harper, Utah|Harper]]. No longer heavily traveled, the rugged canyon road was used mostly for recreation and tourism through the end of the 20th century. The discovery of rich deposits of [[natural gas]] deep beneath the West Tavaputs Plateau has brought an influx of industrial truck traffic since 2002. The large amounts of [[fugitive dust]] produced by the trucks' passage may be damaging the rock art. Public debate is ongoing about how best to balance energy development in the canyon against the preservation of its cultural resources.<ref name=blm/>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Nine Mile Creek at North Franks Canyon, Utah.jpg|thumb|Ninemile Canyon (the dark green area at the bottom) at North Franks Canyon. An array of natural gas wells is visible in the distance, May 2019.]]\n\nNinemile Canyon runs roughly southwest to northeast, with numerous winding turns, just to the north of the [[Book Cliffs]], and south and east of [[Ashley National Forest]]. The full {{convert|78|mi|adj=on}} canyon route, formerly [[Utah State Route 53 (1931-1969)|SR&#8209;53]] through Gate Canyon, connects the towns of [[Wellington, Utah|Wellington]] and [[Myton, Utah|Myton]]. Nine Mile Creek, the [[stream]] that formed the canyon, is by no means a major body of water. Its importance lies in the fact that it is one of the few water sources in the region that are reliable year-round, and it has been so since prehistoric times. Nine Mile Creek is actually a minor [[tributary]] of the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]], emptying into [[Desolation Canyon]] on the east. A number of tributary canyons branch off Ninemile Cayon itself, including Argyle Canyon, Cottonwood Canyon, [[Minnie Maud]], and Dry Canyon. Significant rock art sites are frequently located near the junctions where they meet the main canyon.\n\n==Archaeology==\n[[File:HuntSceneNMC.JPG|thumb|left|The famous ''Cottonwood Panel'', also called ''The Great Hunt'', May 2006]]\n\nThere are at least an estimated 1,000 rock art sites in the canyon, with more than 10,000 individual images.<ref name=spangler/>{{rp|141}} The true figures may be ten times as high,<ref name=dirtraker/> but there is no question that rock art is more concentrated here than anywhere else in [[North America]]. Much is in the form of pecked [[petroglyph]]s, and there are many painted [[pictograph]]s as well. Researchers have also identified hundreds of [[pit-house]]s, rock shelters, and [[granary|granaries]], although only a limited amount of [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]] has been carried out. Many of these structures are located high above the canyon floor on cliff ledges, pinnacles, and [[mesa]]s. They were built by the Fremont, whose presence in Ninemile Canyon has been dated at AD 950\u20131250. Indeed, Ninemile Canyon was one of the locations most heavily occupied by the Fremont.<ref name=carbon/><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.riversimulator.org/Resources/History/UtahCounties/HistoryOfCarbonCounty1996Watt.pdf|title=A History of Carbon County|last=Watt|first=Ronald G.|publisher=|year=|isbn=0-913738-15-8|location=|pages=14\u201316|format=PDF}}</ref> In contrast to the purely [[hunter-gatherer]] cultures that surrounded them, the Fremont practiced [[agriculture]], growing [[maize|corn]] and [[squash (plant)|squash]] along the canyon bottom. Compared to other Fremont areas, relatively little [[pottery]] is found in Nine Mile, suggesting that [[bean]]s, which must be boiled for hours to become edible, were not an important part of the local diet.<ref name=spangler />{{rp|45}} The Fremont left [[irrigation]] ditches and earthen lodges on the canyon floor that could be seen as late as the 1930s, but are no longer visible after generations of modern cultivation.<ref name=spangler />{{rp|21}}\n\n[[File:Utebison.jpeg|thumb|The prints under this [[bison]]'s hooves indicate Ute origin, November 2007.]]\nBy the 16th century the ancestral Utes were in the canyon. They added to the rock art already on the walls, but in styles of their own. Many scenes, for example, depict Ute hunters on horseback and date to the 1800s. Despite the number of Ute [[artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] found in Nine Mile, there is no archaeological evidence of any Ute camps or residences.<ref name=spangler />{{rp|55\u201357}}\n\n{{anchor|DuchesneNineMileCanyonARs|CarbonNineMileCanyonARs}}\n\n===Archaeological sites===\n[[File:Redman Village Nine Mile Canyon.jpeg|thumb|left|Stone shelter at Redman Village, April 2007]]\n\nIn 2009, 63 archaeological sites in the canyon were listed on the U.S. [[National Register of Historic Places]], 36 in Carbon County and 27 in Duchesne County. Most are named in the National Register listing only by their [[Smithsonian trinomial]] codes, but there were three named sites in Carbon County: Cottonwood Village, Drop-Dead Ruin, and First Canyon Site. The named ones in Duchesne County are Centennial House, Fool's Pinnacle, Karen's Cist, Maxies Pad, Nordell's Fort, Redman Village, Sunstone Village, and Taylor's City. The locations and details of these sites are not disclosed by the National Register.<ref name=nrhp1/> The 63 sites include 40 Fremont constructions, 19 rock art sites, and 4 sets of historical-era dwellings.<ref name=nom/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=&itype=ngpsid|title=Utah rock art canyon up for historic designation|last=Stark|first=Mike|date=November 11, 2009|website=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> A further 165 sites were added on September 12, 2012, all of them designated by codes only. Of these additional listings, 158 are in Carbon County and 7 in Duchesne County. On September 22, 2014, 101 more sites were added, all in Carbon County.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pregnantbuffalo.jpeg|thumb|left|Rock art from [[Archaic period in the Americas|Archaic]] to modern, November 2007]]\n\nThere is some evidence that American [[fur trapper]]s may have entered the canyon in the early 19th century, but the first unequivocal sign of a white presence is an inscription on the canyon wall reading \"S. Groesbeck August 19, 1867\".<ref name=spangler />{{rp|62}} [[John Wesley Powell]]'s second [[Colorado River]] expedition camped at the mouth of the canyon in 1871, and the earliest appearance of the name ''Nine Mile Canyon'' is in records of the expedition.<ref name=spangler />{{rp|15}}\n\nNine Mile Canyon Road (also 9 Mile Canyon Road) was constructed through the canyon in 1886 by the [[Buffalo Soldiers]] of the [[9th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|9th Cavalry Regiment]], linking [[Fort Duchesne]] to the railroad through the city of [[Price, Utah|Price]]. Use of the road surged in 1889 after the discovery of [[Gilsonite]] in the [[Uinta Basin]]. This was the main transportation route in eastern Utah until well into the 20th century. Most of the [[stagecoach]], mail, freight, and [[telegraph]] traffic into the Uinta Basin passed through Ninemile Canyon until after the arrival of the [[Uintah Railway]] around 1905.\n\nThe freight trade led to the settlement of the canyon itself. One of the main stagecoach stops developed into a town of sorts. Called [[Harper, Utah|Harper]], it included a hotel, store, school, and an unofficial post office. It lacked a formal town site, simply taking in a long stretch of scattered ranches and buildings. The community grew gradually from the 1880s until it was officially established as the town of Harper in 1905. The Harper precinct as a whole had a population of 130 at its peak in 1910,<ref name=duchesne/>{{rp|81\u201382}} but in the early 1920s Harper became a [[ghost town]].<ref name=guide/>\n\n==Current issues==\n[[File:Defacedelk.jpeg|thumb|Defaced rock art in Rasmussen Cave, April 2007]]\n\nRock art and other ancient artifacts are now protected by law and, although enforcement is difficult, outright [[looting]] and malicious [[vandalism]] are largely a thing of the past. Ninemile Canyon's rock art, however, is still at risk. Carved and painted mainly on weathered [[sandstone]] panels, the images are susceptible to [[erosion]], which is accelerated by touching<ref name=spangler />{{rp|87}} and airborne dust. The dust is a special concern as heavy industrial traffic in the canyon increases.\n\nNine Mile Canyon Road, once such an important route, was almost completely [[pavement (material)|unpaved]] until 2013. In fact, it was considered the poorest of the four old military roads in Duchesne County.<ref name=duchesne />{{rp|71}} In 1990, the U.S. [[Bureau of Land Management]] (BLM) designated it as a Scenic Backcountry Byway.<ref name=risk/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=&itype=ngpsid|title=Nine Mile Canyon at risk|last=Henetz|first=Patty|date=February 16, 2008|website=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> The Ninemile Canyon Paving project is expected to be complete in October 2014 (weather permitting).\n\n===Natural gas development===\n[[File:Nine Mile Canyon Compressor Station.jpeg|thumb|left|Bill Barrett Corporation's natural gas compressor station, at the Dry Canyon junction, March 2008]]\n\nNine Mile's unique archaeological resources have led to intense debate over [[land use]]. As in many rural areas of the Western United States, land in the canyon is a patchwork of [[public land|public]] and private property. Archaeological sites are found on both. Commercially important deposits of [[mineral]]s and other geological resources have also been discovered, further complicating the issues. Since 2002, the [[Bill Barrett Corporation]], in cooperation with the BLM and private landowners, has been pursuing a natural gas exploration project on the West Tavaputs Plateau in and around the canyon. The company estimates the available natural gas reserves at approximately 1 trillion cubic feet (2.8{{e|10}} m\u00b3).<ref name=risk/> Bill Barrett Corporation has spent some $2 million on improving area roads, and the complete project, if approved as planned, could create as many as 1000 jobs.<ref name=oversight/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303182831/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/content/mobile/700231011/Canyon-oversight-questioned.html?printView=true|title=Canyon oversight questioned {{!}} Deseret News|last=Thalman|first=James|date=2016-03-03|website=[[Deseret News]]|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> Government involvement in the project has been controversial, drawing complaints from [[conservation movement|conservation]] groups that not enough is being done to protect natural and cultural resources.<ref name=policy/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/13/us/when-the-bush-energy-policy-confronts-ancient-art.html|title=When the Bush Energy Policy Confronts Ancient Art|last=Barringer|first=Felicity|date=2004-06-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nine Mile Canyon dust.jpeg|thumb|Road dust drifts up the canyon, March 2008.]]\n[[File:Dustypetroglyphs.jpeg|thumb|Dust-covered petroglyphs,<br>March 2008]]\nPrevious to 2013, industrial truck traffic on Nine Mile's main road were producing clouds of dust. Prior to paving, the dirt road was not maintained for heavy traffic.<ref name=risk/> The dust reduced visibility on the road and settled on the rock art. Carbon County, which supervises the use of the road, approved the application of [[magnesium chloride]] on the road as a [[dust abatement]] measure. The compound pulled moisture from the air to dampen dust, but it may have done more harm than good<ref name=dust/> as the magnesium chloride dust may have drifted on to the rock walls.<ref name=risk/> A 2007 study, commissioned by the BLM and paid for by Bill Barrett Corporation,<ref name=oversight/> found that the dust that lands on a rock art panel created \"a very serious conservation problem.\" <ref name=dust/>\n\nIn 2004, due to concerns about energy development and increasing recreational and tourist traffic, Ninemile Canyon was named on the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]]'s list of [[America's Most Endangered Places]].<ref name=nthp/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525040903/http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/sites/mountains-plains-region/nine-mile-canyon.html|title=Nine Mile Canyon|date=2012-05-25|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> In 2009, 63 sites in the canyon were added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]],<ref name=nrhp1/> with another 164 added in 2012<ref name=nrhp2/> and 101 in 2014, and the BLM has announced plans to nominate some 600 more in years to come.<ref name=nom/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Carbon County, Utah]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Duchesne County, Utah]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em|refs=\n\n<ref name=blm>{{